1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,820
Hello everyone. We are HydroSat Systems.
Our Track 2 project turns multispectral satellite observations into actionable water-quality information.

2
00:00:06,820 --> 00:00:15,913
We approached this challenge as an onboard decision-system problem,
not only as a pure regression task.

3
00:00:15,913 --> 00:00:27,280
The question for us was:
how can a satellite ingest mounted point requests and run bounded local inference

4
00:00:27,280 --> 00:00:39,783
while downlinking compact turbidity and chlorophyll-a products
quickly enough to support real decisions?

5
00:00:39,783 --> 00:00:47,740
The final architecture is modular and practical.

6
00:00:47,740 --> 00:00:56,833
First, the container reads the mounted point tables
and the multispectral scene bundle.

7
00:00:56,833 --> 00:01:05,927
Second, it extracts a 24 by 24 local patch for each requested coordinate,
so we avoid full-scene processing on the critical path.

8
00:01:05,927 --> 00:01:16,157
Third, we generate a large feature set
with spectral bands, water indices, ratios, spatial summaries, and seasonal metadata.

9
00:01:16,157 --> 00:01:25,250
Fourth, we run target-specific ensemble regressors,
apply runtime calibration, and write the required Track 2 JSON outputs.

10
00:01:25,250 --> 00:01:34,912
We deliberately kept the default runtime CPU-first.

11
00:01:34,912 --> 00:01:45,710
The frozen runtime model bundle is about 4.8 megabytes,
and the default path does not depend on runtime downloads or mandatory CNN inference.

12
00:01:45,710 --> 00:01:56,508
On this local machine, the full released Area8 evaluation
covers 475 points in about 25.2 seconds.

13
00:01:56,508 --> 00:02:10,717
That gives us a practical reference for execution time, artifact footprint,
deployment simplicity, and a bounded, auditable satellite-ground workflow.

14
00:02:10,717 --> 00:02:20,947
A ground-first pattern often prioritizes
sending full imagery down first and interpreting it later.

15
00:02:20,947 --> 00:02:32,882
Our design is different.
We compute point-centered spectral-spatial descriptors and keep separate targets

16
00:02:32,882 --> 00:02:44,817
so turbidity and chlorophyll-a can follow their own feature importance patterns,
while heavier CNN work stays off the default path.

17
00:02:44,817 --> 00:02:59,025
On top of that deployable baseline, we propose a site-adaptive layer
that can use historical same-station measurements once a basin is under active monitoring.

18
00:02:59,025 --> 00:03:08,687
The strongest evidence in the final repository
is that we keep two questions separate.

19
00:03:08,687 --> 00:03:19,485
For the frozen competition-style runtime,
we use the official released Area8 evaluator and reach a reproducible algorithm score of 14.58.

20
00:03:19,485 --> 00:03:30,852
For the stronger monitored-basin concept,
post-release retrospective date-held-out research reached 53.95

21
00:03:30,852 --> 00:03:40,513
after adding same-site temporal calibration.
The first number is leaderboard-comparable.

22
00:03:40,513 --> 00:03:50,175
The second shows why the mission design
is more ambitious than the frozen benchmark model alone.

23
00:03:50,175 --> 00:04:00,405
Our roadmap starts from a compact frozen baseline
and a stronger adaptive direction.

24
00:04:00,405 --> 00:04:11,203
First, we want to productionize the site-adaptive layer
with uncertainty-aware fallbacks.

25
00:04:11,203 --> 00:04:22,570
Second, we want to test causal forward-only adaptation
for near-real-time operations and improve turbidity robustness under shift.

26
00:04:22,570 --> 00:04:32,800
Third, we want to extend the pipeline
toward regime-aware routing and selective downlink.

27
00:04:32,800 --> 00:04:41,325
The important point is that the current repository is already runnable,
and the roadmap builds on that instead of replacing it.

28
00:04:41,325 --> 00:04:51,555
HydroSat Systems is a two-person build team.

29
00:04:51,555 --> 00:05:01,785
Arv Bali led the modeling direction, submission ownership,
and final proposal narrative.

30
00:05:01,785 --> 00:05:12,583
Mrinank handled evaluation tooling, late-stage experiment infrastructure,
environment setup, runtime integration, and packaging.

31
00:05:12,583 --> 00:05:22,813
Together, our goal was to deliver not only a leaderboard attempt,
but a compact and credible onboard inference baseline.

32
00:05:22,813 --> 00:05:33,043
Thank you for listening.
HydroSat now delivers a reproducible frozen runtime at 14.58

33
00:05:33,043 --> 00:05:41,000
and a clearer path toward site-adaptive water-quality intelligence
as monitoring history accumulates.
